l.w: unpledgedThe OED lists "unpledged bowl" as (n. poetic Obsolete) "a drinking bowl whose contents have been poisoned," and cites one other instance, from 1823: S. Rogers Italy 160 "For deeds of violence..came the unpledged bowl, The stab of the stiletto." To "pledge" a person was to to drink with or to him or her as a gesture of fidelity, goodwill, etc. (Christopher Francese <francese@dickinson.edu>, Dickinson College)
